"The sea is ours": inland Bolivia hopes the court will reopen the way to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors are guarding the naval headquarters in La Paz, which is decorated with ropes.
Above public buildings there is a blue flag in the color of the ocean.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca for the Amazon are described by the motto: “The sea is ours.
Obtaining it is our duty.”
Across inland Bolivia there is still a vivid memory of the coast that the country lost to Chile in the bloody resource war of the 19th century – as well as the desire to re-cross the Pacific Ocean.
These desires are perhaps the biggest in several decades, as Bolivia awaits a decision from the international court, which is due to fall on October 1 after five years of negotiations.
“Bolivia has the energy, the spirit of unity and peace, and of course it expects a positive result,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will be watching the MSD decision on big screens across the country in the hope that the Hague tribunal will decide in favor of Bolivia’s claim that – after many decades of interrupted talks – Chile is obliged to act on granting Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
The charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, Evo Morales, who is facing a controversial battle for re-election next year, is also very interested in Monday’s decision.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will decide in favor of Bolivia – and even if it did, it would not change much.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands has no power to assign Chilean territory to anyone and said it would not determine the outcome of any possible talks.
The fact that the MSD’s decision comes just six months after the latest arguments were heard shows that the case “was not complicated,” according to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And for the past four years, not only have they not supported the cause of Bolivia, but they may have slowed it down.
“The current Bolivian government has taken over the issues of access to the sea,” says Zárate.
He adds that Morales’ attacking rhetoric has weakened all of Chile’s remaining goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will one day start to act again, but after that it will be extremely difficult to hold discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltze, a representative of Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision was unusually quick.
On Monday, it will bring Bolivia “an exceptional opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance “to end 139 years of disagreement with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also refused to use Morales – still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America – the question of the sea as a political cliffhanger.
“Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The verdict is an opportunity to discover that we need to deal with the past.”
