John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have achieved a number of academic successes and this continues in 2018 with other excellent test results. Individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community activities only underline this.
The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) represents more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland and strives to provide the best level of service to its pupils and parents.
Independent schools prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement individually tailored school education plans, we observe that modern languages are still popular and sought-after subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes straight to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is a significant observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year’s exams show that languages are at the top of the tables, with independent schools having the highest rate of success.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language achieved the best grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that the highest grade A was achieved by 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by students are equally valued in the curricula of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17 percent of job vacancies are insufficient language skills, for reasons that employers cite as a problem.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job opportunities require languages, these skills are a necessity in a globalized world.
Whatever career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have the real advantage of having such a lifelong skill in the future.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages automatically gains an advantage over the competition.
According to a 2013 survey conducted by YouGov among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, with the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, namely 15 percent, being French.
Therefore, it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
If children learn more languages, especially those of emerging economies, they will be more likely to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school is different in what languages it teaches.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK in the run-up to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child is interested in, he will always have a choice of several languages at independent schools with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At this point, there is no denying that languages are essential in the global business environment for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should in fact be considered as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and attraction.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
