North Korea says it will not disarm unilaterally and without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister said on Saturday that continuing U.N. sanctions had deepened its mistrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country would never give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said at his annual general meeting that North Korea had taken “significant measures of goodwill” in the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"But we do not see an appropriate response from the United States," he said.
Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such circumstances it is not possible to disarm unilaterally.
While Ri reiterated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for each step, his statement appeared significant in that he did not reject the timilion for unilateral denuclearization.
Ri mentioned a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the U.S. president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on “denuclearizing the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised North Korea security assurances.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 war, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States is insisting on ‘denuclearization first’ and increasing the pressure on sanctions to enforce its objectives, and even opposing ‘declaring an end to war’,” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader stressed at the U.N. earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea and not the United States were on the side of denuclearization, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come into such a bleak situation.”
However, Rih’s tone was dramatically different from last year’s, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that North Korea’s missile targeting of U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea’s “total destruction,” praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said much work still needs to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is completely wiped out.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a time frame for it, saying, “If it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
