Harvard students attend a course designed to teach them to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has forced all of its students to sleep more, in an effort to fight the growing culture of macho studios all night long, where students don’t sleep and are encouraged with caffeine.
Academics have found that students at the world’s most famous university are often helpless when it comes to the basics of caring for themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, which he believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this only now, in my final year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students basic information about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were really not sleeping during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of student colleges where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleep habits.
In another part, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that students’ behavior will not change immediately.
However, we believe they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in “studying all night long” still exists, he added, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is also growing.
Enough good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because sleep deprivation switches the brain to a mode of starvation, so a person is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that he took in one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push the whole course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
The professor advised students to consider setting the alarm for the time to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting that can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to problems with falling asleep.
